---
import CaseStudy from '../../layouts/CaseStudy.astro';

const diagPlatform = `flowchart LR
    subgraph Devices ["10M+ Wearable Devices"]
        A["Health Sensors\\nHR · SpO2 · Steps\\nAccelerometer · Sleep"]
    end

    subgraph Ingestion ["Real-time Ingestion"]
        B["Apache Kafka\\n2B+ events/month\\nunder 5s lag"]
    end

    subgraph Processing ["Stream and Batch Processing"]
        C["Python Consumers\\nEvent normalization\\nStream aggregation"]
        D["AWS Lambda\\nEvent-driven handlers\\nAlert triggers"]
    end

    subgraph Storage ["Data Layer"]
        E[("MongoDB\\nHealth time-series\\nUser + device profiles")]
        F[("DynamoDB\\n10k concurrent requests\\nSession and device state")]
        G[/"S3\\nRaw event archive\\nBatch replay buffer"/]
    end

    subgraph ML ["Analytics and ML"]
        H["Feature Pipelines\\nPython · NumPy · Pandas"]
        I["ML Model Serving\\nHealth insight inference\\nAnomaly detection"]
        J["Health Analytics\\nUser-facing dashboards\\nPartner reporting"]
    end

    A -->|"real-time"| B
    B --> C & D
    C --> E & G
    D --> F
    E & G --> H
    H --> I & J

    style B fill:#2997ff,color:#fff,stroke:#0077ed`;

const diagDataFlow = `flowchart TD
    RAW["Raw Sensor Events\\nPulse · motion · SpO2\\nhigh-frequency, unvalidated"]
    --> KAFKA["Kafka Topic\\nPartitioned by device_id"]
    --> CONSUMER["Python Consumer\\nParse · validate · normalize"]
    --> BRANCH{Event type}

    BRANCH -->|"health metric"| MONGO["MongoDB\\ntime-series collection\\nindexed by user_id + timestamp"]
    BRANCH -->|"session state"| DYNAMO["DynamoDB\\ndevice + session state\\nlow-latency reads"]
    BRANCH -->|"raw archive"| S3["S3\\nParquet — daily partitions\\nbatch ML training data"]

    MONGO & S3 --> FEATURE["Feature Extraction\\nwindowed aggregations\\nPandas + NumPy"]
    FEATURE --> MODEL["ML Inference\\nhealth score · anomaly flag\\nrecovery index"]`;
---

<CaseStudy
  title="KaHa Wearable Platform"
  subtitle="The data infrastructure behind a health wearable platform serving 10M+ users — Kafka ingestion at 2B+ events/month, Python stream processing, and a multi-store data layer built for real-time ML inference."
  tags={['Apache Kafka', 'Python', 'AWS', 'MongoDB', 'DynamoDB', 'NumPy', 'Pandas']}
  githubUrl=""
>

  <div class="cs-section">
    <h2>Context</h2>
    <p>
      KaHa Technologies builds the firmware and data platform that powers white-label health
      wearables — smartwatches and fitness bands sold under various consumer brands. The platform
      sits between the device and whatever health app the brand has built: it ingests raw
      sensor data, processes it, runs ML inference for health insights, and delivers results
      to the brand's app in near real-time.
    </p>
    <p>
      At the time I joined, the platform was scaling fast — device activations were growing and
      the existing architecture was starting to show lag. The job was to build an ingestion and
      processing layer that could handle 2B+ monthly events across 10M+ active devices without
      data lag exceeding 5 seconds.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="cs-section">
    <h2>Platform Architecture</h2>
    <p>
      Devices publish sensor events to Kafka. Python consumers process the stream in near real-time,
      routing each event type to the right datastore. A separate batch layer handles feature extraction
      for ML model training and serving.
    </p>
    <pre class="mermaid" set:text={diagPlatform}></pre>
  </div>

  <div class="cs-section">
    <h2>Data Flow Detail</h2>
    <p>
      Every raw event passes through the same normalization step before branching — this keeps
      the storage layer clean regardless of device firmware version or sensor calibration differences
      between hardware partners.
    </p>
    <pre class="mermaid" set:text={diagDataFlow}></pre>
  </div>

  <div class="cs-section">
    <h2>Key Engineering Decisions</h2>

    <div class="adr-card">
      <span class="decision">Decision #1 — Message Queue</span>
      <h3>Why Kafka over SQS or direct writes?</h3>
      <p>
        Direct writes to a database at 2B events/month create a thundering herd problem —
        spikes in device activity (morning workouts, sleep tracking start times) create write
        bursts that overwhelm any single datastore. Kafka absorbs those spikes. Consumer lag
        becomes visible and manageable; the datastore never sees raw burst load. SQS could
        absorb bursts too, but Kafka's log retention and consumer group model gave us the
        ability to replay events for ML retraining and to onboard new consumers (e.g., a new
        analytics pipeline) without touching the producers. That replay capability paid off
        several times during model iteration.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="adr-card">
      <span class="decision">Decision #2 — Storage Split</span>
      <h3>Why MongoDB + DynamoDB + S3 instead of one datastore?</h3>
      <p>
        The three data access patterns are genuinely different. Health time-series (heart rate
        over a 30-day window, sleep stages per night) maps naturally to MongoDB's document model
        with time-indexed collections. Session and device state (is this device online? what's
        its last sync timestamp?) needs single-digit millisecond reads — that's DynamoDB's job.
        Raw event archive for ML batch training doesn't need low latency at all; it needs cheap,
        durable storage with efficient range reads — that's S3 Parquet. Forcing any one of these
        patterns into a general-purpose datastore would have meant either overpaying or accepting
        worse performance on two of the three use cases.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="adr-card">
      <span class="decision">Decision #3 — Feature Extraction</span>
      <h3>Why batch feature extraction over in-stream computation?</h3>
      <p>
        The ML models for health insights (recovery index, activity classification, anomaly
        detection) require windowed features — heart rate variability over the past hour, step
        count compared to a 7-day baseline. Computing these windows in-stream is theoretically
        possible but adds significant state management complexity to the consumer. In practice,
        the insight latency requirement was minutes, not seconds — users don't need their
        recovery score the instant they wake up; they need it by the time they open the app.
        Batch feature extraction on S3 Parquet archives kept the stream consumers simple and
        made the feature engineering code easy to iterate on without touching the ingestion layer.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="cs-section">
    <h2>Scale and Constraints</h2>
    <p>
      The hardest constraint wasn't raw throughput — Kafka handles that. It was device heterogeneity.
      KaHa's platform runs on hardware from multiple OEM partners, each with slightly different
      sensor firmware, sampling rates, and data formats. The normalization layer in the Python
      consumer had to handle all of these consistently, and new device variants showed up
      regularly. Keeping that logic maintainable — without making every new device a production
      incident — required disciplined schema versioning and a test suite that covered the
      known edge cases from each hardware partner.
    </p>
    <p>
      The 5-second lag target sounds easy until you account for device connectivity patterns.
      Wearables aren't always online — they buffer locally and sync in batches when a phone
      is nearby. The pipeline had to handle out-of-order events gracefully, since a batch of
      buffered readings from 20 minutes ago arriving at once is normal, not an error.
    </p>
  </div>

</CaseStudy>
